[ChapterName "Exercise 3: Yugoslav destruction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/6VkLbgOl"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3q1r2/5pkp/r1p1p1p1/p2p3n/4P3/2N2P2/PPPQ2P1/2KR3R w - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this 5+0 lichess blitz game, white has sacrificed the h pawn in the Yugoslav attack.

It's our turn to take over. What is the cleanest path to victory? }
16. g4! (16. Rxh5?? $17 { An interesting idea, but this sacrifice is highly unclear in this position since we have already traded so many pieces. } 16... gxh5 17. Rh1 h4! $17 { Black should have no problems at all here since the g file remains closed. }) 16... Nf6 { Ng3 directly lost the knight to Qh6+ Kf6, Qh4+. } (16... Ng3 17. Qh6+ Kf6 18. Qh4+ $18 { Just as hopeless. }) 17. Qh6+ (17. e5? { Premature, after Ng8! black defends some of the weakened dark squares. }) 17... Kg8 { Nice job so far! Using the open h file and weakened dark squares, we've infiltrated with the heavy pieces on the kingside.
Only one more precise move is needed to seal the deal. } 18. e5! { Exactly! The knight cannot safely move anywhere without allowing Qxh7#. } (18. g5?? { A common mistake in the Yugoslav attack. After Nh5! the h file remains closed, and the attack is going nowhere. } 18... Nh5 19. Rxh5 $13) *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Exercise 4: Tactical infiltration"]
[Date "2009.06.25"]
[White "Vladimir Akopian"]
[Black "Joel Lautier"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 4: Tactical infiltration"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/O9dXDP8b"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1bq1bppp/p7/2p5/N3p3/1P6/PBP1QPPP/3RR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Here we have a more recent game where black has a weakened pawn structure in exchange for the bishop pair.

Are there any targets on the kingside that black is hard pressed to defend? }
1. Qg4! g6 { Defending mate with Bf6 would have lost the bishop to Bxf6, so black is forced into making this weakening move. } (1... f6? 2. Rd7 Qc8 3. Nb6 $18 { Loses just as in the game except now we also have a weakened 7th rank we can use as well. }) (1... Bf6?? 2. Bxf6 $18 { The g pawn is pinned. }) 2. Rd7 (2. Qd7?! { Another good move since the queen cannot be captured without losing a bishop. But is there a point after Rfc8? } 2... Rfc8 (2... Qxd7?? 3. Rxd7 $18 { [%cal Gd7e7,Gd7b7] }) 3. Nb6! { The only real way forward. } 3... Qxb6 4. Qxe7 $16 { With Qe5 next, white is still in the driver's seat. }) 2... Qc8 { Lautier is desperate to defend his dark squared bishop for fear of the famous "death by dark square" strategy! This tricky pin temporarily prevents us from snacking on the e7 bishop. } 3. Nb6! { Exactly! The queen cannot maintain this pin, and so black will be losing the important dark squared bishop next. In the game, Akopian finished brilliantly after Qc6 with Nd5! winning a clean piece since Bd8??, Rxd8! Rfxd8, Ne7+ leads to instant destruction on the dark squares. } (3. Rxe7?? { Oh no, our queen! } 3... Qxg4 $19) (3. Red1!? $18 { Also strong, but we're still not threatening to take out this dark squared bishop unless we next play the move played in the game. }) (3. Qh3!? $18 { Also strong, but we really want to capture the e7 bishop and keep queens on the board. }) *


[Event "1944 Georgian Championship"]
[Date "1944"]
[White "Malashkhia"]
[Black "Tigran V Petrosian"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 5: Slay the dragon"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/utD9f5DK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2ppbp/3p2p1/5P2/3BP1n1/2N5/PqP1Q2P/3R1RK1 w - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Another dragon! This time we're facing against a 15 year old Tigran Petrosian, soon to become a master, and 20 years before he becomes world champion.

Let's teach Petrosian a lesson on the importance of the dark squared bishop in the dragon! }
17. f6! { A beautiful interference shot! Now that the bishops are not staring at each other, the knight on g4 is truly hanging. } (17. Qxg4?? { This was surely what Petrosian had calculated. Now after Bxd4+ Rxd4, the c3 knight is hanging, and black is winning. } 17... Bxd4+ 18. Rxd4 Qxc3 $19) (17. Bxg7?? { After Kxg7, we still have to deal with the fact that our c3 knight is hanging. } 17... Kxg7 18. Qxg4 Qxc3 $19) (17. e5?? { After Nxe5, black has just won another pawn and has no issues in his position. } 17... Nxe5 $17) 17... Bxf6 { The only way for black to maintain the tension between the bishops. } (17... Nxf6!? { This interesting alternative also loses: } 18. Nd5! Qxa2 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Rxf6 $18 { Another way for white to break through on the dark squares. }) (17... exf6? 18. Qxg4 $18) 18. Rxf6! (18. Bxf6?? { After Nxf6, black is up 3 pawns and keeps his safe king. } 18... Nxf6 $19) (18. Qxg4?? { This was surely what Petrosian had calculated. Now after Bxd4+ Rxd4, the c3 knight is hanging, and black is winning. }) (18. Nd5?? { After Bxd4+, Rxd4 Qxd4+, everything collapses with check. } 18... Bxd4+ 19. Rxd4 Qxd4+ $19) 18... Nxf6 { Sacrificing the exchange leaves white with the only dark squared bishop on the board. Now finish Petrosian off! } 19. Nd5 { Brilliantly done! The black queen is attacked and cannot defend e7. After e7 drops, black will soon lose the knight on f6 next with a ferocious attack on the dark squares. Petrosian resigned and allowed his opponent a miniature rather than limp along for another few moves.
Hilariously, Petrosian himself became famous for his exchange sacrifices later in his career. No doubt this exchange sacrifice left a strong impression on him! } *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: An important Stonewall idea"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "An important Stonewall idea"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/IV54dIxt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp4pp/2pbpn2/3p1p2/2PP4/1P3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ Weak color complexes create positional ideas as well.

In the Stonewall Dutch, black builds a strong fortification on the central light squares, in exchange for having a poor c8 bishop, and potentially weak dark squares. If black is not careful in this position, they can quickly end up positionally worse by making the next move carelessly. }
7... O-O?! { A normal developing move, but it misses white's main idea. } (7... Qe7! $10 { Black should first prevent white's main idea before castling. }) 8. Ba3! { Trading off black's main defender of the dark squares ensures that white will have good control over the weakened dark squares across the board. e5, c5, and f4 in particular are the most central squares soon under white's control.
Notice how white is using their understanding of good and bad bishops ( https://lichess.org/study/kNn68T8l/467VfNtg ) to make favorable trades. } 8... Bxa3 { PRO TIP: Understanding the pawn structure of your openings will help you identify exactly which piece trades are beneficial or harmful to your position! } 9. Nxa3 $14 { Maneuvering this a3 knight to d3 (which can then jump to all the important central dark squares) takes time, but gives white a good game.
The following moves are not forced, but there is one more follow-up idea in this position worth seeing. } 9... Qe7 10. Nc2 Nbd7 11. Qc1 Ne4 12. Qa3! $14 { Not the only idea, but certainly one that continues the dark square strategy! If the queens are traded, then white inches that much closer to a dream good knight (on e5) vs bad bishop (on c8) endgame. If the queens are not traded, then black must cede further control of the dark squares to white. } *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Maximizing piece activity"]
[Site "Mar del Plata"]
[Date "March 31, 1966"]
[Round "15"]
[White "Leonid Stein"]
[Black "Samuel Schweber"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "IM"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Maximizing piece activity"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/rzpEeuuM"]
[FEN "r3kn1r/p1q1npp1/4p3/1p1pP1Np/b1pP3P/2P3PB/2PB1P2/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has a huge space advantage, a safe king, and the bishop pair. However, black is up a pawn with a solid position. The only real issue in black's position is that every single fixed pawn is stuck on a light square, and he's missing his dark squared bishop. }
1. Bc1! { Always retreat! Stein correctly recognizes that he needs to activate his bad bishop previously stuck behind the central pawn chain. } 1... g6 { Without a dark squared bishop, black can never challenge white's dark squared bishop, which can poke and prod the dark squares along any diagonal it wants. } 2. Ba3 { The previously inactive bishop now breathes fire along the uncontested a3-f8 diagonal. } { [%cal Ba3f8] } 2... Nh7 { PRO TIP: When you are being attacked, trade pieces. Attacks with less pieces are less likely to succeed. } 3. Nf3! $16 { Just as we should not trade active bishops for inactive bishops, we do not trade the active knight on g5 for the passive knight on h7.
Stein is clearly better and can launch an attack on Schweber's king no matter which side of the board he ends up residing, as in the game: https://lichess.org/ztgf1ASG#41 } *


[Event "14th Ljubljana Open"]
[Date "2003.06.22"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Matej Susnik"]
[Black "Milos Pavlovic"]
[Result "*"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Weakening the center"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/klOcPnT0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1p2ppbp/2bp1np1/p7/2PBP3/2N2P2/PP1QB1PP/2R2RK1 b - - 1 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We arrive at a common position in the accelerated dragon, Maroczy bind variation. Black is cramped for space, but has good play on the queenside and center. Black's next move may be surprising. }
13... Nd7! { Has black gone insane? Surely trading the dark squared bishops means black's king will be permanently weakened?
Incorrect! Nd7 is perfectly correct because (1) white has no pieces that can even attack the kingside, and (2) white will actually be the one left with weakened dark squares in the center! Let's see how this works: } 14. Bxg7?! (14. Be3! $14 { Keeping this important dark square defender alive is necessary if white wants to claim an advantage in this position. }) 14... Kxg7 15. Rfd1 (15. Qd4+ f6 $10 { With Qb6 coming next to trade the queens, it should be clear that black is not weak on the kingside dark squares. }) 15... Qb6+ { Further infiltrating the weakened dark squares. } 16. Qd4+?! { Trading one of the few remaining pieces that can control the dark squares cannot be correct. } (16. Kh1 { A better try. } 16... Nc5 $10 { But white's terrible light squared bishop remains a problem piece. } { [%csl Gc5,Re2] }) 16... Qxd4+ 17. Rxd4 Nc5 $15 { Look at how terrible white's light squared bishop is. Compare it to how strong black's knight is on the (dark squared!) outpost c5. The center of the board is swiss cheese on the dark squares.
To fully appreciate how bad this position is for white, enjoy GM Milos Pavlovic's smooth conversion of this position here: https://lichess.org/eQ9o4949/black#33 } { [%csl Gc5,Re2] } *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Sacrificing material to weaken a color complex"]
[Date "08.2021"]
[White "Vladimir Fedoseev"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Sacrificing material to weaken a color complex"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/Ca5TbP8a"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r1bq1r2/pp2p1bk/3p2p1/P2Pnp1p/4P2P/R1N1BP2/1P1QBP2/4K2R b K - 3 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We join a tense King's Indian middlegame between Fedoseev and Carlsen from the 2021 World Cup. In this position, Magnus uncorks a deep positional sacrifice to win control of the dark squares for the rest of the game. }
16... f4! { Stopping white from playing f4, thereby keeping all of white's pawns fixed on light squares. } (16... Bd7?! 17. f4 Ng4 18. Bd4 $14 { Still an unclear position, but trading dark squared bishops leaves black's king a little more vulnerable. }) 17. Bxf4 { But isn't this just a pawn for Fedoseev? } 17... Bd7 { Carlsen calmly finishes development before revealing the point of the pawn sacrifice. } 18. Nd1 { The knight retreats so that the a3 rook can defend f3 directly. White is exactly one move away from Bg5 and completely consolidating... } { [%cal Ba3f3] } (18. Be3? { The bishop cannot simply retreat to prepare f4 due to tactical issues on f3: } 18... Rxf3! 19. Bxf3?? Nxf3+ $19 { [%cal Gf3d2,Gf3e1] }) 18... Rxf4!! { What a beautiful idea! White's main defender of the weakened dark squares is taken out, even at the cost of a pawn and an exchange. } 19. Qxf4 Bh6 { The bishop redirects to the most important diagonal so that white's f4 is stopped permanently. } 20. Qg3 Qf8! { Preventing f4 once again. } 21. Ne3 Bf4! { And it's official. Every one of white's pieces is hopelessly incapable of defending the dark squares on the kingside, queenside, and center. Notice how white's bad bishop is trapped behind the pawn chain, doing nothing. White's king can also be an issue if it castles kingside, since there might be mates on the h2 square. } 22. Qg2 { White is down a queen and bishop until he can prove otherwise. Contrast those poor pieces with black's dominant minor pieces on the centralized dark square outposts. The position is still objectively level, but white went on to collapse quickly as Carlsen won a brilliant game https://lichess.org/2F5ao81q#43.
GM Daniel King's analysis is enlightening: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B3i9RL2uh28 } { [%csl Rg2,Re2,Gf4,Ge5] } *


