[White "Vishwanathan Anand"]
[Black "Vasyl Ivanchuk"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 6: Finding the correct trade"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/y4ytXwPW"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "q1r3k1/1b1nbpp1/r2p1n1p/p3pP2/NpP1P3/1B4N1/PPR1QBPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. Qd3? { In a tough position, Anand played Qd3, a careless move that misses our positional threat. What did Anand overlook? } (1. h3 $15 { Would have been a better way to prepare Qd3. }) 1... Ng4! $17 (1... Nc5!? { A very different idea than what Ivanchuk had in mind, but also strong. This knight must be captured, after which the open d file proves dangerous for white. } 2. Nxc5 dxc5 3. Ba4 Rd8 $15) 2. Nf1 { Exactly! this simple move wins the dark squared bishop - the most important piece in white's position based on the pawn structure. } (2. Nh5!! { Trading off one knight means that white has potential for a kingside attack, since black is missing a key defensive piece. This amazing defensive resource was missed by both players during the game. } 2... Nxf2 3. Rxf2 Nf6 4. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $15) 2... Nxf2 $17 (2... Ndf6! $17 { Ivanchuk's move in the game is great as well since white's bishop isn't yet able to avoid being traded. Play Nxf2 instead for the solution. } 3. Bg3? Bxe4 $19) (2... Bg5?! $17 { This move allows Bg3, when white can keep his dark squared bishop. }) 3. Rxf2 $17 { After winning the most important defender, Ivanchuk went on to win a brilliant game on the newly weakened dark squares: https://lichess.org/ioWi7jGv/black#46 } *


[Event "1951 USSR Championship"]
[Date "06.1951"]
[White "Vladimir Zak"]
[Black "Rashid Nezhmetdinov"]
[Result "*"]
[BlackTitle "IM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 7: The correct diagonal"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/pmmt6WBz"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r3q1k1/pbn1r1bp/1p1p1np1/2pP2N1/P7/2N1B1PB/1P1Q1P1P/3RR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. Ne6? { We take over the board from famous attacking player Rashid Nezhmetdinov in a complicated Benoni position. His opponent (famed trainer of Spassky and Korchnoi) has just planted a knight on an outpost deep in our territory. What is the best way forward? } 1... Nxe6 (1... Rxe6? { An interesting exchange sacrifice but after dxe6!, Qc6 isn't that effective, since white retains their important light squared bishop. } 2. dxe6 Qc6 3. f3 $16) 2. Bxe6+ { Now the bishop lands with a thud on the supported e6 square. How could this possibly be playable for black? } (2. dxe6!? Qc6 3. f3 Qxf3 $17 { Probably a better line for white than what was played in the game. }) 2... Rxe6! (2... Kh8? $18 { Too flaccid. That e6 monster dominates all of our major pieces. }) (2... Kf8? $18 { Too flaccid. That e6 monster dominates all of our major pieces. }) 3. dxe6 { A necessity. We could not allow that bishop to shut down our major pieces on the e file.
But did we sacrifice the exchange just to end up in a worse position? } 3... Qc6! { Exactly! The e6 pawn is irrelevant. What's more important is forming a battery with our light squared bishop to further target the weakened light squares (g2 and h1) around white's king. Zak resigned in only 3 more moves. } (3... Qxe6? { Probably the move that Zak had expected, but after Qxd6 Qh3, f3 Bxf3, Rd2 defends the mate. White remains up the exchange with a (reasonably) safe king. } 4. Qxd6 Qh3 5. f3 Bxf3 6. Rd2 $10 { If we had formed the battery with the bishop instead, then Qh1+ is immediately devastating here. As is, our queen and bishop are only coordinated on the one light square - g2 - which is defended. }) *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Exercise 8: Clearance"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[White "NoseKnowsAll"]
[Black "GARBANZOS"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 8: Clearance"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/YRpNwv0q"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r3k1nr/p4pp1/npq5/2bpP1Bp/3p3P/1Q3N2/P2N1PP1/1R3RK1 w kq - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We arrive at an interesting position from the Tal variation of the advanced Caro-Kann. White has sacrificed two pawns for a lead in development and has destroyed black's center.

Keeping the theme of this study in mind, what move is dying to be played? }
17. e6! (17. Rbc1!? { A reasonable move, but not one that particularly accomplishes anything concrete. }) (17. Rfc1!? { A reasonable move, but not one that particularly accomplishes anything concrete. }) (17. Qd3?! { After Nc7, we are just forcing black to improve their pieces. }) 17... fxe6 { Obviously Qxe6 would have lost the queen to Rfe1. But what's the point of e6? } (17... Qxe6? 18. Rfe1 $18) (17... f6!? { Probably the best move. } 18. Qd3! fxg5?? 19. Qg6+ Kd8 20. Qxg7 $18 { Wins the trapped rook on h8 with tempo on the knight. }) 18. Ne5! (18. Qd3!? { A strong alternative, but not as precise as in the game. Maneuvering the queen to d3 hits both a6 and g6, so white will have full compensation for being down 3 pawns. But when there's an immediate knockout available, we should really think hard and find it. }) 18... Qb7 { Exactly! e6 further weakened black's light squares and cleared the way for Ne5. Now this knight controls many key light squares in black's camp. Can we finish black off? } 19. Qb5+! (19. Qa4+!? { The right idea, but not as precise as the other (more forcing) check. }) (19. Qh3!? { An interesting idea to further attack the weakened light squares. However, there is a more direct knockout. }) (19. Ne4?! { A hilarious knight move, which probably shouldn't be taken. However, there is a more direct knockout. }) (19. Qd3?! { Too slow. Qg6+ would be fantastic to play. But black has time to stop it while simultaneously developing their kingside pieces with Ne7. } 19... Ne7 $16) 19... Kf8 { Beautiful coordination! The knight, queen, and bishop control nearly every square around black's king. In particular, just look at all of those light square weaknesses. To avoid getting mated, black has to play Kf8 which allows many wins, including the hilarious Ng6+ Kf7, Nxh8+ Kf8, Ng6+ Kf7, Ne5+ winning a full rook before returning to the current position. } { [%csl Bf6,Be7,Bd8,Bd7,Be8,Bc6,Bf7] } *


[Event "1955 Gothenburg Interzonal"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[Round "15"]
[White "Herman Pilnik"]
[Black "Efim Geller"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 9: Aggressive intentions"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/LpEAT6wx"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/3n3p/3p1bp1/2pPpp2/p1P5/2B2P2/PPB1Q1PP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Our position looks promising since white's bishop pair is currently under control. But how to make progress? Which color complex should we be looking to take over? }
1... e4! (1... a3!? { This move does weaken the dark squares further, but it is only good if our follow-up is the same as what was played in the game. } 2. b3 e4! $17) (1... Qe7 $15 { Sensible development, but we have a chance here to take control of the dark squares in this position. }) (1... Kg7? $10 { The king is not safer on this square. }) (1... Rb8? $16 { Oh no, our a pawn! }) (1... f4? $10 { Giving up control over the e4 square is not a good way to begin an attack. After Qe4, black is the one under pressure. }) (1... g5? $18 { Oh no, our f5 pawn! }) 2. Bxf6 (2. f4? Bxc3 3. bxc3 $17 { The passed pawn on e4 is still impressive. }) (2. fxe4!? Bxc3 3. bxc3 f4! $17 { The same idea is strong here too. }) 2... Qxf6 (2... Rxf6 $15 { Not bad, but the rook gets in the way of our queen's route to the kingside dark squares. }) (2... Nxf6?! $10 { The wrong recapture. Our knight from f6 is not able to reach the more important dark square outpost: e5 }) (2... exf3?? { Oops. Qe6+ wins our queen! } 3. Qe6+ $18) 3. fxe4 f4! { The point of our sequence! Sacrificing the potential passed pawn is a thematic way to break through. Now the e5 square is available for the knight, the e4 pawn is a traitor against white's pieces, and we will slowly build up on the kingside dark squares that are now fully under our control. } (3... fxe4?? $18 { Oh no, our queen! }) (3... Qe5?! $15 { This keeps the e pawn, but the knight would prefer to land on this square. }) (3... Qxb2?! { This pawn will always be weak, and after exf5 white's bishop breathes fire towards our newly weakened king. }) (3... Ne5? $16 { The right idea, but let's not give white the chance to play exf5 and open up their light squared bishop. }) *


[Event "Import"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/t2UmBZVq"]
[Date "2017.11.02"]
[White "Hasangatin, R."]
[Black "Shirov, A."]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2502"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2630"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[TimeControl "-"]
[Termination "Normal"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D02"]
[Opening "Queen's Pawn Game: London System"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Shirov executes \"death by dark square\""]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/yVhP3ZrV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ In this beautiful miniature from Alexei Shirov, he essentially refutes greedy play in the London by dominating the dark squares across the board. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Shirov plays one of the soundest ways to "punish" the London - playing like a QGD with colors reversed. } 4. dxc5!? { Accepting the "queen's gambit" } (4. e3 $10 { The most common continuation. }) 4... e6 { Simple development ensure that black should regain the c5 pawn. } 5. b4? { Quite possibly the only true mistake played in this game by white. He greedily tries to hold onto his extra pawn. } (5. e3 Bxc5 $10) 5... a5 { Shirov immediately seeks to break down this dark square pawn chain at all costs. } 6. c3 (6. a3?! axb4! $15 { As long as the rook on a1 remains undefended, the a3 pawn is never actually protecting b4 due to the pin. }) 6... axb4 7. cxb4 Nc6 { Further pressure on the dark square pawn chain. } 8. Qb3 (8. a3? Nxb4 $17 { The same pin ensures white cannot keep the pawn chain together. }) (8. b5? Qa5+ $17 { Regains the pawn with interest. } { [%cal Ga5b5] }) 8... Ne4! { Centralizing the knight on a light square so that it controls key dark squares in white's camp. Qf6 is the threat, forking both the bishop and rook. } 9. Nc3 (9. a3?? Qf6! $19 { Wins a full piece at least. }) (9. Nbd2?? Qf6! $19 { Wins a full piece at least. } { [%cal Gf6f4,Gf6a1] }) (9. e3?? Qf6! { [%cal Gf6a1] } 10. Nd4 Nxd4 11. exd4 Qxf4 $19 { Wins a piece as well. }) (9. Bd2!? { This sad retreating move may be white's best attempt to not lose, but after: } 9... b6! 10. cxb6? (10. e3 bxc5 $17 { Regains black's pawn with interest. }) 10... Qf6! { The destruction of white's dark squares is complete. }) 9... Qf6! { More dark square control! More! } { [%cal Gf6f4,Gf6a1] } 10. Bd2 Nxb4!! { A thunderclap of a move. Shirov's destruction of white's dark square control is complete. } 11. Qxb4 Bxc5 12. Qb5+? { In a hopeless position, white tries to regain lost time before defending f2. } (12. Qb2 Bxf2+ 13. Kd1 Bc5 $17 { Best play, but this position is obviously terrible for white. } { [%cal Ge4f2] }) 12... Bd7! { But Shirov has absolutely none of it. Every tempo matters in this position, and the b7 pawn (and a8 rook!) are irrelevant to black's dark square domination in the center. } (12... Ke7?? 13. Rc1! Bxf2+ 14. Kd1 $10 { No knockout in sight. }) 13. Qxb7 Bxf2+ { And just like that, the remaining dark squares around white's king crumble. } 14. Kd1 Nxc3+! $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { White resigned rather than face the following destruction: } 15. Bxc3 Ba4+!? (15... Qxc3!? { Another aesthetic way to win. } 16. Qxa8+ Ke7 17. Qxh8 Ba4#) 16. Qb3 (16. Kd2 Qf4+ 17. e3 Qxe3#) 16... Bxb3+ 17. axb3 Rxa1+ 18. Bxa1 Qxa1+ $19 0-1


